# SSL Zertifikat erneuern (IIS) 

1. Start the IIS Manager 

2. Select the server name 

3. Open Server Certificates 

4. ![](data:image/png;base64,)

5. In the Actions pane select Create Certificate Request 

6. Fill out the form. The common name is the primary DNS name you will use for your website. 

7. You can submit additional DNS names later if needed 

8. In the Actions pane select Create Certificate Request 

9. Fill out the form. The common name is the primary DNS name you will use for your website. 

10. You can submit additional DNS names later if needed 

11. ![](data:image/png;base64,)

12. Set the Key length to 2048 

13. Save the certificate request on a local drive. 

14. Create a ticket via this link: <https://swatchgroupservices.service-now.com/esc?id=sc_cat_item&sys_id=c38fa613870b4550065585d30cbb352c> 
![](data:image/png;base64,)
1. You will revive the certificate by Email or in the Ticket 

2. Start the IIS Manager 

3. Select the server name 

4. Open Server Certificates 

5. Select in the Action menu Complete Certificate Request 

6. Browse the path to the certificate and enter a friendly name 

7. The old and the new certificates are listed in the Server certificate section on IIS. 

8. That the new certificate will be used by the website you need to change the https binding and select the new certificate to use. 

9. ![](data:image/png;base64,)

10. As cleanup when the website works with the new certificate you can remove the old from Server Certificates 

 

Binding a certificate to a website in IIS means that you are activating the installed digital certificate and associating it with a particular website, port, and/or IP Address. Binding in IIS can be performed by following these simple steps. (These instructions assume that you have already [installed](https://www.ssl.com/how-to/install-an-ssl-tls-certificate-in-iis-10/) your certificate in IIS.) 

1. Start IIS Manager. Start IIS Manager. One quick way to do this is by opening the Run command, then typing inetmgr and clicking the OK button. 

![Run window](data:image/png;base64,)

2. Select website. In the Connections pane on the left side of the window, navigate to the Server and Site you wish to bind the certificate to. 

![Select server and website](data:image/png;base64,)

3. Open bindings. In the Actions pane on the right, click Bindings… 

![Click Bindings](data:image/png;base64,)

4. Click Add… Click the Add… button. 

![Click Add...](data:image/png;base64,)

5. Select binding type. The Add Site Binding window will open. For Type, select https. 

![Select type](data:image/png;base64,)

6. Select IP address. For IP address, select All Unassigned, or the site’s IP address. 

![select IP address](data:image/png;base64,)

7. Enter port. For Port, enter 443. 

![Port](data:image/png;base64,)

8. Select certificate Select the desired certificate from the SSL certificate drop-down menu. 

![select certificate](data:image/png;base64,)

9. View certificate details. You can use the View… button to get details about the selected certificate. 

![View certificate details](data:image/png;base64,)

10. Require Server Name Indication (SNI) if necessary. If you are serving more than one domain name from the same IP address, enter it in the Host name field and check the Require Server Name Indication box. If not, you can safely leave these blank. 

![Host name and SNI](data:image/png;base64,)

11. Close “Add Site Binding” window. Click the OK button to close the window. 

![OK button](data:image/png;base64,)

12. Close “Site Bindings” window. Verify that the binding has been added, then close the Site Bindings window by clicking the Close button. 

![OK button](data:image/png;base64,)

13. Edit existing binding (if necessary). You may can also edit an existing binding. To do this, simply select the item and click Edit. You can change the port, the IP Address, the host name, and the certificate to use. 

![Edit binding](data:image/png;base64,)

 

Aus <<https://www.ssl.com/how-to/binding-in-iis-10/>>

# Automatische Zertifizierungserneuerung

Wir schlagen vor, dass Renata die Zertifikate jeweils selbständig erneuern kann ohne die Mithilfe von Autexis.

Dazu müssen folgende Schritte gemacht werden:

1. Erstellung der Zertifikate, spezifisch für Test- oder Produktiv-System (issued to: renata-mestest.swatchgroup.net für das Testsystem und renata-mes.swatchgroup.net für das Produktivsystem)

2. Testsystem GDC03425: Ablegen der Zertifikate unter D:\DEV\keys als «certificate.pem» und «key.pem». Die beiden Files vor dem Ersetzen in den backup-Ordner kopieren, damit im Fehlerfall auf diese zurückgegriffen werden kann.  
   ![](file:///tmp/lu3442292btke.tmp/lu3442292btn1_tmp_fb3bc595.png)

Produktivsystem GDC03424: Ablegen der Zertifikate unter D:\DEV\keys als «renata-mes.swatchgroup.net.pem» und «renata-mes.swatchgroup.net\_key.pem». Die beiden Files vor dem Ersetzen in den backup-Ordner kopieren, damit im Fehlerfall auf diese zurückgegriffen werden kann.  
![](file:///tmp/lu3442292btke.tmp/lu3442292btn1_tmp_76ffe5ec.png)

3. Neustart des MES-Service: Da der Service jeden Abend kurz nach Mitternacht neu startet kann dieser Schritt weggelassen werden. Alternativ kann dies auch durch einen Neustart des Servers gemacht werden.
